# Vercel Speed Insights Installation Report

## Summary
Successfully verified and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the FFC App project.

## What Was Done

### 1. Documentation Review
- Fetched the latest official Vercel Speed Insights documentation from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart
- Confirmed framework-specific instructions for Next.js App Router (13.5+)

### 2. Package Installation
- The `@vercel/speed-insights` package (v2.0.0) was already present in package.json
- Ran `pnpm install` to ensure all dependencies were properly installed
- Verified the package is now correctly available in node_modules

### 3. Code Configuration
- The SpeedInsights component was already imported and configured in the root layout file
- Fixed import ordering to comply with ESLint perfectionist/sort-imports rules
- Moved Vercel imports (@vercel/analytics/next and @vercel/speed-insights/next) to appear before MUI imports

### Files Modified
- **FRONTEND/src/app/layout.tsx**: Reordered imports to satisfy linter requirements
  - Moved `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next'` and `import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/next'` to come before MUI imports
  - The `<SpeedInsights />` component was already properly placed in the root layout before body closing tag

### 4. Testing & Verification
- ✅ **Build**: Successfully completed production build with no errors
- ✅ **Linter**: Fixed import ordering issue; no new errors introduced (20 pre-existing warnings remain in other files)
- ✅ **Tests**: All tests pass (1/1 test passed)
- ✅ **Lock Files**: pnpm-lock.yaml is up to date

## Implementation Details

According to the official Vercel documentation, for Next.js 13.5+ with App Router:
1. The SpeedInsights component should be imported from '@vercel/speed-insights/next'
2. It should be placed in the root layout file
3. It should be rendered inside the body tag

The implementation follows these guidelines perfectly:
```tsx
import { SpeedInsights } from '@vercel/speed-insights/next';

export default async function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <html>
      <body>
        {/* ... other components ... */}
        <SpeedInsights />
      </body>
    </html>
  );
}
```

## Next Steps

To enable Speed Insights on Vercel:
1. Navigate to your Vercel dashboard
2. Select "Speed Insights" from the sidebar
3. Choose your project
4. Click the "Enable" button
5. Deploy the application
6. Verify the `/_vercel/speed-insights/*` routes are accessible after deployment
7. Monitor performance metrics in the Speed Insights dashboard

